00:24:13.310 --> 00:24:13.320
Okay.

00:24:13.320 --> 00:24:15.270
Let's get started.

00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:16.870
Welcome

00:24:16.880 --> 00:24:19.870
the PufferLib 1.0 launch.

00:24:19.880 --> 00:24:22.630
It's a product project

00:24:22.640 --> 00:24:26.110
not a product, all open source.

00:24:26.120 --> 00:24:28.150
Project I'm fully excited to bring to

00:24:28.160 --> 00:24:29.830
you guys.

00:24:29.840 --> 00:24:31.910
I've been working on this for a while.

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:34.790
At least full-time since I graduated.

00:24:34.800 --> 00:24:35.990
And this is something that I really

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.030
think is going to change

00:24:38.040 --> 00:24:39.750
the way that we look at reinforcement

00:24:39.760 --> 00:24:41.150
learning.

00:24:41.160 --> 00:24:43.950
Not going to be anything big or flashy.

00:24:43.960 --> 00:24:45.470
Really just a small set of low-level

00:24:45.480 --> 00:24:47.350
tools, but it's going to make a big

00:24:47.360 --> 00:24:50.150
difference in how easy it is to just do

00:24:50.160 --> 00:24:53.550
work in reinforcement learning.

00:24:53.560 --> 00:24:55.790
Want to keep this preamble short.

00:24:55.800 --> 00:24:59.230
Today is not about talking heads.

00:24:59.240 --> 00:25:00.710
It's about

00:25:00.720 --> 00:25:03.230
a bunch of quick tech demos

00:25:03.240 --> 00:25:04.510
and uh

00:25:04.520 --> 00:25:06.430
going with this stuff can do.

00:25:06.440 --> 00:25:07.470
So, the only thing is I'm going to start

00:25:07.480 --> 00:25:09.710
with are where you can get all of these

00:25:09.720 --> 00:25:12.790
demos and run them yourselves, as what

00:25:12.800 --> 00:25:15.030
I'm running them on.

00:25:15.040 --> 00:25:16.190
So,

00:25:16.200 --> 00:25:17.350
what you see right here with the little

00:25:17.360 --> 00:25:20.070
pufferfish prompt, this is puffer tank.

00:25:20.080 --> 00:25:22.710
It is a container. We ship pre-built

00:25:22.720 --> 00:25:25.590
images with a good version of PyTorch

00:25:25.600 --> 00:25:27.830
and Python, plus all the annoying to

00:25:27.840 --> 00:25:30.190
install dependencies. Not for pufferlib,

00:25:30.200 --> 00:25:32.110
pufferlib doesn't have any, but for all

00:25:32.120 --> 00:25:33.470
of the environments that I'm going to be

00:25:33.480 --> 00:25:36.150
using. It makes it a lot easier. You've

00:25:36.160 --> 00:25:38.070
got like a little hook, so if you use VS

00:25:38.080 --> 00:25:40.030
Code, it's super easy. As you can see,

00:25:40.040 --> 00:25:41.670
I'm not doing that. It's also very easy

00:25:41.680 --> 00:25:43.230
just in a console.

00:25:43.240 --> 00:25:44.470
Um

00:25:44.480 --> 00:25:47.030
so, if you see I'm in this puffer tank

00:25:47.040 --> 00:25:49.510
repos puffer tank folder right now.

00:25:49.520 --> 00:25:51.710
You can get this on GitHub

00:25:51.720 --> 00:25:56.110
/pufferai/puffertank.

00:25:57.310 --> 00:25:57.320
Container's a little bit beefy, but

00:25:57.320 --> 00:26:04.950
that's just PyTorch and Python.

00:26:21.230 --> 00:26:21.240
Second, just muting uh

00:26:21.240 --> 00:26:22.550
extra mics

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:28.110
on the Zoom call.

00:26:29.950 --> 00:26:29.960
Okay.

00:26:29.960 --> 00:26:31.590
You can get this right here.

00:26:31.600 --> 00:26:33.350
pufferai puffertank

00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:35.910
and

00:26:35.920 --> 00:26:37.230
you can also get it on Docker Hub

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:42.870
pufferai/puffertank tag 1.0.

00:26:44.230 --> 00:26:44.240
Starts up the container, and then the

00:26:44.240 --> 00:26:45.870
box that I'm running this on, I messed

00:26:45.880 --> 00:26:48.830
this HT into a desktop.

00:26:48.840 --> 00:26:54.310
This is a 13900K.

00:26:57.470 --> 00:26:57.480
with a single 4090. So, it's a nice

00:26:57.480 --> 00:27:00.230
desktop, but it's a desktop. No 800s, no

00:27:00.240 --> 00:27:02.710
800s, nothing.

00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:05.150
So, the first thing that I'm going to do

00:27:05.160 --> 00:27:07.750
is I'm going to

00:27:07.760 --> 00:27:10.470
start in PufferLib, which is included,

00:27:10.480 --> 00:27:12.990
run some of the examples. I'm going to

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:14.790
start with really the thing that

00:27:14.800 --> 00:27:16.950
motivated PufferLib and the solution

00:27:16.960 --> 00:27:18.670
that I found to it. And then you're

00:27:18.680 --> 00:27:22.630
going to see how this one very small

00:27:22.640 --> 00:27:24.950
wrapper is going to make everything so

00:27:24.960 --> 00:27:29.510
much easier.

00:27:32.150 --> 00:27:32.160
So, this is CleanRL's PPO Atari. I see

00:27:32.160 --> 00:27:34.790
we have Costa uh in the chat on YouTube.

00:27:34.800 --> 00:27:37.430
Amazing, amazing project.

00:27:37.440 --> 00:27:40.670
So, I'm using it to uh improve over

00:27:40.680 --> 00:27:42.750
because it's the best thing not to like

00:27:42.760 --> 00:27:49.670
smash it as a baseline.

00:27:52.350 --> 00:27:52.360
2800 or so steps per second, so close to

00:27:52.360 --> 00:27:54.670
3,000. And then uh the difference

00:27:54.680 --> 00:28:00.550
between this script and vanilla

00:28:03.790 --> 00:28:03.800
So, the original, all I did was I added

00:28:03.800 --> 00:28:05.710
uh multiprocessing vectorization from

00:28:05.720 --> 00:28:07.910
Gymnasium, just so that uh it would use

00:28:07.920 --> 00:28:10.030
multiple cores, and then I fixed uh an

00:28:10.040 --> 00:28:12.470
unnecessary copy. And just so you can

00:28:12.480 --> 00:28:14.590
see that I did actually improve it so

00:28:14.600 --> 00:28:16.110
that we're using a stronger baseline,

00:28:16.120 --> 00:28:20.310
not a weaker one.

00:28:23.710 --> 00:28:23.720
The original is between 1,200 and 1,500

00:28:23.720 --> 00:28:25.590
steps per second, depending on the

00:28:25.600 --> 00:28:27.630
temperature where this desktop is. It is

00:28:27.640 --> 00:28:31.430
currently in Florida.

00:28:34.270 --> 00:28:34.280
So, what happens now if we want to run

00:28:34.280 --> 00:28:36.630
this same sort of a script, this same

00:28:36.640 --> 00:28:39.670
PPL, on a more complex, interesting

00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:41.670
environment like NetHack, or we'll use

00:28:41.680 --> 00:28:43.870
MiniHack for this.

00:28:43.880 --> 00:28:45.510
Well,

00:28:45.520 --> 00:28:51.350
we shouldn't have to change very much.

00:28:57.950 --> 00:28:57.960
You're going to get rid of all these

00:28:57.960 --> 00:29:00.230
Atari wrapper imports, add the MiniHack

00:29:00.240 --> 00:29:01.350
ones,

00:29:01.360 --> 00:29:02.990
change the M string, set a reasonable

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:04.390
batch size,

00:29:04.400 --> 00:29:06.150
get rid of all these junk Atari

00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:07.830
wrappers,

00:29:07.840 --> 00:29:09.910
add some MiniHack stuff. It just needs a

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:11.990
compatibility wrapper for

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:14.830
the latest version of Gymnasium.

00:29:14.840 --> 00:29:15.710
And then we're going to add in a

00:29:15.720 --> 00:29:17.870
MiniHack network.

00:29:17.880 --> 00:29:18.870
So,

00:29:18.880 --> 00:29:20.230
the only other changes I have other than

00:29:20.240 --> 00:29:22.870
this are moving a couple lines down a

00:29:22.880 --> 00:29:24.950
little bit for demonstration purposes,

00:29:24.960 --> 00:29:27.910
and uh changing the data type to match

00:29:27.920 --> 00:29:29.870
MiniHack. So, assuming that you already

00:29:29.880 --> 00:29:32.150
have a network suitable for MiniHack,

00:29:32.160 --> 00:29:38.110
this is 5, maybe 10 minutes of work.

00:29:39.750 --> 00:29:39.760
Unfortunately, this is not going to

00:29:39.760 --> 00:29:41.350
work.

00:29:41.360 --> 00:29:42.950
We have the error right here, which is

00:29:42.960 --> 00:29:49.030
line 191.

00:29:50.310 --> 00:29:50.320
And we can see that CleanRL is

00:29:50.320 --> 00:29:51.550
allocating a big tensor for

00:29:51.560 --> 00:29:53.030
observations.

00:29:53.040 --> 00:29:54.910
This works fine for Atari and many

00:29:54.920 --> 00:29:56.630
simpler environments that just have flat

00:29:56.640 --> 00:29:58.710
observations like this. But many of the

00:29:58.720 --> 00:30:00.790
more complex and interesting ones have

00:30:00.800 --> 00:30:02.510
structured observations. Some of them

00:30:02.520 --> 00:30:04.510
even have structured actions.

00:30:04.520 --> 00:30:05.750
So,

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:08.430
that means that in order to actually use

00:30:08.440 --> 00:30:11.310
CleanRL for something like MiniHack,

00:30:11.320 --> 00:30:13.070
you're going to have to modify this obs

00:30:13.080 --> 00:30:14.670
to be a big dictionary with a whole

00:30:14.680 --> 00:30:15.910
bunch of different types, whole bunch of

00:30:15.920 --> 00:30:17.590
different shapes and data. And then

00:30:17.600 --> 00:30:19.830
anywhere that you use obs, you're going

00:30:19.840 --> 00:30:22.230
to have to

00:30:22.240 --> 00:30:24.230
make the appropriate changes.

00:30:24.240 --> 00:30:26.670
So,

00:30:26.680 --> 00:30:27.990
you're not going to be able to just dot

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:30.070
cuda these here cuz it's a dictionary.

00:30:30.080 --> 00:30:31.350
Tensor dict and other stuff help with

00:30:31.360 --> 00:30:32.550
this, but still you're going to have to

00:30:32.560 --> 00:30:35.790
do some extra work.

00:30:37.030 --> 00:30:37.040
Here, you're not going to be able to do

00:30:37.040 --> 00:30:40.150
this because it's a dictionary.

00:30:40.160 --> 00:30:41.990
Down here as well. Pretty much anywhere

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:43.710
you use obs, you're going to add a whole

00:30:43.720 --> 00:30:46.430
bunch of extra logic. Now, sure this is

00:30:46.440 --> 00:30:48.190
just like a little bit of engineering,

00:30:48.200 --> 00:30:49.670
but I can tell you from experience and

00:30:49.680 --> 00:30:50.990
anybody else who's worked with these

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:52.910
more complex environments can tell you

00:30:52.920 --> 00:30:54.350
that this is just not a place that you

00:30:54.360 --> 00:30:56.070
want to add complexity. It's

00:30:56.080 --> 00:30:58.390
error-prone, it's really janky, it makes

00:30:58.400 --> 00:31:00.190
this code really hard to use for other

00:31:00.200 --> 00:31:02.830
projects and such, and this is often

00:31:02.840 --> 00:31:05.030
sufficient motivation to just like not

00:31:05.040 --> 00:31:07.190
want to use minihack. And even if you do

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:09.950
all of this, it can be pretty slow.

00:31:09.960 --> 00:31:12.350
So,

00:31:12.360 --> 00:31:14.350
we could also just do PufferPPO

00:31:14.360 --> 00:31:24.390
minihack.

00:31:26.590 --> 00:31:26.600
And now we're training minihack

00:31:26.600 --> 00:31:29.910
at high 30 high 3,000s, close to 4,000

00:31:29.920 --> 00:31:32.750
steps per second.

00:31:32.760 --> 00:31:34.070
So, what did I change in order to make

00:31:34.080 --> 00:31:35.950
this happen? Did I just go make all of

00:31:35.960 --> 00:31:44.150
those changes and do it anyways?

00:31:46.430 --> 00:31:46.440
I added one wrapper.

00:31:46.440 --> 00:31:47.790
And it's not a minihack wrapper, it's a

00:31:47.800 --> 00:31:49.910
gymnasium wrapper. A wrapper that will

00:31:49.920 --> 00:31:51.710
work for whatever gymnasium environment,

00:31:51.720 --> 00:31:53.590
almost any that we support.

00:31:53.600 --> 00:31:55.270
Doesn't have to be added individually

00:31:55.280 --> 00:31:56.790
either. It's just, you know, a pretty

00:31:56.800 --> 00:31:58.550
good subset of gymnasium envs that will

00:31:58.560 --> 00:32:00.710
soon be all of gymnasium envs.

00:32:00.720 --> 00:32:02.150
And then, yeah, there's one like one

00:32:02.160 --> 00:32:04.310
extra line with the agent uh creation

00:32:04.320 --> 00:32:07.030
function that'll go away in a moment.

00:32:07.040 --> 00:32:08.630
So, how do we do all of this with one

00:32:08.640 --> 00:32:12.030
wrapper? How do we make this just work?

00:32:12.040 --> 00:32:14.350
I'm going to open up on the right-hand

00:32:14.360 --> 00:32:16.670
side

00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:21.390
this demo file.

00:32:29.550 --> 00:32:29.560
Here we can see the observation space of

00:32:29.560 --> 00:32:31.750
minihack. It is a mess.

00:32:31.760 --> 00:32:33.390
You have a whole bunch of different

00:32:33.400 --> 00:32:35.110
elements in this dictionary. They're

00:32:35.120 --> 00:32:37.270
boxes with different shapes. They even

00:32:37.280 --> 00:32:40.190
have different data types.

00:32:40.200 --> 00:32:41.870
And now, if we look at what happens once

00:32:41.880 --> 00:32:43.950
we wrap it with puffer,

00:32:43.960 --> 00:32:46.990
it is just about 13,000 uint8, so 13

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:50.310
kilobytes of flat data.

00:32:50.320 --> 00:32:51.630
Now, you might think that sure, anybody

00:32:51.640 --> 00:32:52.950
can write a quick flatten wrapper.

00:32:52.960 --> 00:32:54.950
That's like 10 lines of code. No big

00:32:54.960 --> 00:32:56.030
deal.

00:32:56.040 --> 00:32:57.350
Uh and that the problem with that is

00:32:57.360 --> 00:32:59.150
going to be that these 13,000 bytes

00:32:59.160 --> 00:33:01.110
aren't particularly useful because you

00:33:01.120 --> 00:33:03.030
need the structure of this when you go

00:33:03.040 --> 00:33:04.270
to run your data through a network.

00:33:04.280 --> 00:33:05.310
You're not just going to run your

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:08.470
network on flat bytes like this.

00:33:08.480 --> 00:33:10.350
This is where the magic happens.

00:33:10.360 --> 00:33:13.150
And there isn't much magic at all.

00:33:13.160 --> 00:33:15.430
It's really just a NumPy feature that is

00:33:15.440 --> 00:33:19.950
a little bit lesser known.

00:33:22.270 --> 00:33:22.280
PufferLib infers this based on the

00:33:22.280 --> 00:33:24.110
observation space.

00:33:24.120 --> 00:33:26.150
This looks very similar and this this

00:33:26.160 --> 00:33:28.230
stick but this dictionary

00:33:28.240 --> 00:33:30.710
is special. This is a valid NumPy data

00:33:30.720 --> 00:33:31.870
type.

00:33:31.880 --> 00:33:33.430
This means that you can make a NumPy

00:33:33.440 --> 00:33:35.830
data array with this data type.

00:33:35.840 --> 00:33:37.510
And NumPy is going to create something

00:33:37.520 --> 00:33:39.230
like a C struct for you.

00:33:39.240 --> 00:33:41.550
This is contiguous memory and it can be

00:33:41.560 --> 00:33:44.630
viewed either as flat bytes or with this

00:33:44.640 --> 00:33:46.510
structure.

00:33:46.520 --> 00:33:49.390
So, for demonstration purposes,

00:33:49.400 --> 00:33:50.910
this is the wrapped environment, so this

00:33:50.920 --> 00:33:52.510
is going to be 13 kilobytes of flat

00:33:52.520 --> 00:33:53.550
data.

00:33:53.560 --> 00:33:54.870
And we're just going to dot view this

00:33:54.880 --> 00:33:57.870
data using this data type right here,

00:33:57.880 --> 00:33:59.910
this dictionary.

00:33:59.920 --> 00:34:01.990
And we can see that we recover the

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:04.750
original data from the flattened form

00:34:04.760 --> 00:34:06.950
with all of the associated data types.

00:34:06.960 --> 00:34:08.430
And this is a view operation that does

00:34:08.440 --> 00:34:09.909
not have to copy. It is incredibly

00:34:09.919 --> 00:34:12.389
quick.

00:34:14.110 --> 00:34:14.120
This also works for vectorized data. So,

00:34:14.120 --> 00:34:15.510
if I'm going to make a VecEnv right

00:34:15.520 --> 00:34:17.830
here,

00:34:17.840 --> 00:34:19.310
we reset the environment to get the flat

00:34:19.320 --> 00:34:20.149
one,

00:34:20.159 --> 00:34:21.550
and then we're going to dot view it to

00:34:21.560 --> 00:34:23.110
get the structured obs.

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:24.830
This actually gives you

00:34:24.840 --> 00:34:26.550
batched data in the exact format that

00:34:26.560 --> 00:34:28.230
you would want it.

00:34:28.240 --> 00:34:32.310
4 by 13 kilobytes goes to 4 by whatever

00:34:32.320 --> 00:34:34.550
the sub temps or dimensions are.

00:34:34.560 --> 00:34:36.590
And this works for

00:34:36.600 --> 00:34:38.149
nested dictionaries, should work for

00:34:38.159 --> 00:34:39.629
tuples, works for lots of different data

00:34:39.639 --> 00:34:40.710
types.

00:34:40.720 --> 00:34:43.590
Um, it's very general.

00:34:43.600 --> 00:34:44.669
Now,

00:34:44.679 --> 00:34:48.750
this is a very, very simple idea. It

00:34:48.760 --> 00:34:50.669
went through many, many iterations to

00:34:50.679 --> 00:34:52.149
get it to this. I didn't even know about

00:34:52.159 --> 00:34:54.030
the NumPy thing when I started making

00:34:54.040 --> 00:34:55.270
this and I had my own custom

00:34:55.280 --> 00:34:57.270
implementations for a while,

00:34:57.280 --> 00:34:58.430
but

00:34:58.440 --> 00:35:00.750
it's incredibly powerful

00:35:00.760 --> 00:35:01.910
because

00:35:01.920 --> 00:35:04.470
it allows you to not have to care about

00:35:04.480 --> 00:35:06.710
structured data in your vectorization

00:35:06.720 --> 00:35:08.110
implementation,

00:35:08.120 --> 00:35:09.670
in CleanRL,

00:35:09.680 --> 00:35:11.430
or anywhere else other than in the

00:35:11.440 --> 00:35:13.190
environment itself,

00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:15.670
and in the forward function of your

00:35:15.680 --> 00:35:17.350
model, right before you need the data

00:35:17.360 --> 00:35:19.950
just in time.

00:35:19.960 --> 00:35:21.150
And there're going to be a little bit of

00:35:21.160 --> 00:35:23.470
uh of additional detail required for

00:35:23.480 --> 00:35:25.550
that forward function, but really it's

00:35:25.560 --> 00:35:27.390
what you see here.

00:35:27.400 --> 00:35:29.350
So, you can write your vectorization

00:35:29.360 --> 00:35:31.670
assuming that you have flat data and

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:33.550
it's going to work not just for Atari,

00:35:33.560 --> 00:35:35.670
but for anything.

00:35:35.680 --> 00:35:39.230
And you can write your CleanRL code, you

00:35:39.240 --> 00:35:40.630
can actually leave it exactly the way it

00:35:40.640 --> 00:35:42.870
is and run MiniHack.

00:35:42.880 --> 00:35:45.470
But making this assumption,

00:35:45.480 --> 00:35:47.910
you can optimize a whole bunch of things

00:35:47.920 --> 00:35:49.430
along the way. So, not only is it going

00:35:49.440 --> 00:35:51.030
to be simpler, it's going to be way

00:35:51.040 --> 00:35:56.310
faster.

00:35:58.190 --> 00:35:58.200
I'm going to run the PufferVec uh

00:35:58.200 --> 00:36:00.230
Puffer's vectorization. So, same code

00:36:00.240 --> 00:36:01.670
with Puffer's vec.

00:36:01.680 --> 00:36:03.350
And now, instead of 4,000 steps per

00:36:03.360 --> 00:36:04.390
second,

00:36:04.400 --> 00:36:06.430
we're over 8,000.

00:36:06.440 --> 00:36:08.270
And the environment itself will run it

00:36:08.280 --> 00:36:10.510
over 50,000 with MiniHack because it has

00:36:10.520 --> 00:36:13.790
some slow wrappers or at around 100,000

00:36:13.800 --> 00:36:16.470
with NetHack.

00:36:16.480 --> 00:36:18.110
You're very much bottlenecked by the

00:36:18.120 --> 00:36:20.790
model here in CleanRL. But over 2x

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:22.310
performance for a drop-in and just to

00:36:22.320 --> 00:36:32.350
show you that it is a drop-in,

00:36:33.910 --> 00:36:33.920
That's all I changed.

00:36:33.920 --> 00:36:35.830
I swapped the vectorization.

00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:36.990
And as you can see, this annoying

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:41.470
signature went away.

00:36:43.790 --> 00:36:43.800
So, this is what is IC is going to allow

00:36:43.800 --> 00:36:46.710
us to just move RL onto more complex and

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:48.470
interesting environments and make it

00:36:48.480 --> 00:36:50.710
very easy to do so. But, let's say that

00:36:50.720 --> 00:36:52.270
you're a researcher or a hobbyist

00:36:52.280 --> 00:36:53.390
working on something where you don't

00:36:53.400 --> 00:36:54.630
really need all these structured

00:36:54.640 --> 00:36:57.150
features just yet. And you know, maybe

00:36:57.160 --> 00:36:59.270
you just want some speed ups on Atari or

00:36:59.280 --> 00:37:00.950
some classic environments. And then

00:37:00.960 --> 00:37:02.670
later on, if it's convenient, you'll

00:37:02.680 --> 00:37:05.310
think about moving to more complex and

00:37:05.320 --> 00:37:06.870
interesting ends.

00:37:06.880 --> 00:37:08.470
Uh you know, if it's convenient to do so

00:37:08.480 --> 00:37:09.830
and if they're faster and if it makes

00:37:09.840 --> 00:37:10.910
sense.

00:37:10.920 --> 00:37:12.990
Well, we actually have some speed ups

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:15.470
even for the simplest case. So, remember

