00:47:03.400 --> 00:47:04.990
BufferLib introduces a Python

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:07.750
implementation of EnvPool.

00:47:07.760 --> 00:47:09.470
EnvPool's a project that allows you to

00:47:09.480 --> 00:47:10.630
run

00:47:10.640 --> 00:47:12.230
more environments than you need per

00:47:12.240 --> 00:47:14.390
batch, such that the ones that you don't

00:47:14.400 --> 00:47:16.430
currently have observations from are

00:47:16.440 --> 00:47:17.990
running in the background while your

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:20.950
model is doing its forward pass. So,

00:47:20.960 --> 00:47:22.710
you can drive your environment time down

00:47:22.720 --> 00:47:25.710
to zero, technically, if uh it only

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:28.030
takes the time of your forward pass.

00:47:28.040 --> 00:47:29.990
This is where the other 2x performance

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:32.070
improvement comes from. And the crucial

00:47:32.080 --> 00:47:34.070
thing with BufferLib is that it will

00:47:34.080 --> 00:47:36.110
work for just about any environment,

00:47:36.120 --> 00:47:37.830
compared to the original EnvPool

00:47:37.840 --> 00:47:39.590
project, which requires you to have

00:47:39.600 --> 00:47:42.390
bound C++ implementations for your

00:47:42.400 --> 00:47:44.030
environments.

00:47:44.040 --> 00:47:46.190
