00:54:13.360 --> 00:54:16.110
at a high level, the major optimizations

00:54:16.120 --> 00:54:18.430
in vectorization that make it this fast

00:54:18.440 --> 00:54:19.750
are the assumption on PufferLib

00:54:19.760 --> 00:54:23.470
emulation, so you only handle flat data.

00:54:23.480 --> 00:54:26.030
Observations are allocated as big

00:54:26.040 --> 00:54:28.230
tensors in shared memory.

00:54:28.240 --> 00:54:30.190
So, the workers will write directly into

00:54:30.200 --> 00:54:31.990
that shared memory without having to

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:34.470
ever stack or concatenate data.

00:54:34.480 --> 00:54:36.910
We support multiple environments per

00:54:36.920 --> 00:54:38.350
process, so you don't crowd too many

00:54:38.360 --> 00:54:40.150
processes.

00:54:40.160 --> 00:54:42.430
The workers themselves,

00:54:42.440 --> 00:54:44.230
they don't rely on pipes for the most

00:54:44.240 --> 00:54:47.310
part or queues for sending data around.

00:54:47.320 --> 00:54:49.630
They actually busy wait on values in

00:54:49.640 --> 00:54:51.230
shared memory, which completely

00:54:51.240 --> 00:54:53.030
eliminates interprocess overhead cuz

00:54:53.040 --> 00:54:55.190
they're just waiting on a value to

00:54:55.200 --> 00:54:58.750
change that is not locked or anything.

00:54:58.760 --> 00:55:02.110
And infos are aggregated over episodes

00:55:02.120 --> 00:55:03.830
by default. That's one of the wrappers

00:55:03.840 --> 00:55:07.110
that we have. And we only will send the

00:55:07.120 --> 00:55:08.670
summed infos

00:55:08.680 --> 00:55:10.190
once per episode, and that's the only

00:55:10.200 --> 00:55:11.790
time that you have to pipe anything.

00:55:11.800 --> 00:55:14.110
That's to save like 40 microseconds or

00:55:14.120 --> 00:55:15.430
whatever, but it makes a big difference

00:55:15.440 --> 00:55:17.310
for fast environments.

00:55:17.320 --> 00:55:18.390
Those are all of the major

00:55:18.400 --> 00:55:20.590
optimizations. Heck, I'll be happy to

