01:00:53.720 --> 01:00:56.070
crazy stuff they do to handle structured

01:00:56.080 --> 01:00:57.990
observations natively. They're going to

01:00:58.000 --> 01:00:59.790
be able to trigger their much better

01:00:59.800 --> 01:01:01.990
tested code paths that are used for like

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:04.110
Atari and stuff. Uh and that's generally

01:01:04.120 --> 01:01:06.070
one of the biggest benefits of pufferlib

01:01:06.080 --> 01:01:08.230
is even if you have a framework that

01:01:08.240 --> 01:01:10.350
technically supports uh all this

01:01:10.360 --> 01:01:12.430
structured stuff on paper, you trigger

01:01:12.440 --> 01:01:14.190
the simplest and most common code path

01:01:14.200 --> 01:01:16.270
that is tested against Atari when you

01:01:16.280 --> 01:01:18.590
use our wrapper. And you can get a lot

01:01:18.600 --> 01:01:20.190
of uh speed improvements as a result

01:01:20.200 --> 01:01:21.670
because usually the more complicated

01:01:21.680 --> 01:01:23.870
code paths are not as well optimized.

01:01:23.880 --> 01:01:26.070
So, there is still a benefit, yes.

01:01:26.080 --> 01:01:27.990
When you have a heavy framework like

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:30.870
